<subSubSection pageId="110" pageNumber="111" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="110.[151,1436,687,965]" pageId="110" pageNumber="111">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,273,831,856]" pageId="110" pageNumber="111">Notes.</emphasis>
Specialist on 
<taxonomicName box="[436,563,832,856]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Asteraceae" kingdom="Plantae" order="Asterales" pageId="110" pageNumber="111" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="family">Asteraceae</taxonomicName>
. This cavity-nester has been studied in 
<collectingRegion box="[1015,1132,831,856]" country="United States of America" name="Wisconsin" pageId="110" pageNumber="111">Wisconsin</collectingRegion>
(
<bibRefCitation author="Medler" box="[1148,1312,831,856]" firstAuthor="Medler" pageId="110" pageNumber="111" pagination="918 - 921" refId="ref94493" refString="Medler, J. T. (1964 a) A note on Megachile (Sayapis) pugnata pugnata Say in trap-nests in Wisconsin (Hymenoptera: Megachilidae). The Canadian Entomologist, 96, 918 - 921. https: // doi. org / 10.4039 / ent 96918 - 6" type="journal article" year="1964" yearSuffix="a">Medler 1964a</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="Medler &amp; Lussenhop" firstAuthor="Medler" pageId="110" pageNumber="111" pagination="1 - 80" refId="ref94805" refString="Medler, J. T. &amp; Lussenhop, J. F. (1968) Leafcutter bees of Wisconsin. University of Wisconsin Research Bulletin, 274, 1 - 80." type="journal article" year="1968">Medler &amp; Lussenhop 1968</bibRefCitation>
). In 
<collectingRegion box="[391,448,868,893]" country="United States of America" name="Utah" pageId="110" pageNumber="111">Utah</collectingRegion>
, it has been explored for its potential as a managed pollinator of commercial sunflower (
<bibRefCitation author="Tepedino &amp; Frohlich" box="[158,469,903,928]" firstAuthor="Tepedino" pageId="110" pageNumber="111" pagination="269 - 274" refId="ref104068" refString="Tepedino, V. J. &amp; Frohlich, D. R. (1982) Mortality factors, pollen utilization, and sex ratio in Megachile pugnata Say (Hymenoptera: Megachilidae), a candidate for commercial sunflower pollination. Journal of the New York Entomological Society, 90, 269 - 274." type="journal article" year="1982">Tepedino &amp; Frohlich 1982</bibRefCitation>
). 
<taxonomicName box="[490,710,903,928]" class="Insecta" family="Megachilidae" genus="Megachile" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="110" pageNumber="111" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="pugnata">
<emphasis box="[490,710,903,928]" italics="true" pageId="110" pageNumber="111">Megachile pugnata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is commonly found in trap-nests placed in both MSU campus, East Lansing, 
<collectingRegion box="[310,418,940,965]" country="United States of America" name="Michigan" pageId="110" pageNumber="111">Michigan</collectingRegion>
and prairie restorations in the LP (JG, pers. obs.).
</paragraph>
